116b2dd0-1440-11e9-b43e-456ed9f9b823	MADAMA BUTTERFLY presented by UK Opera Theatre	madama-butterfly-presented-by-uk-opera-theatre	f	[{"end_time": "2019-03-01 22:00:00", "start_time": "2019-03-01 19:30:00", "optional_title": ""}]	https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/infinite-industries-event-images/uploads/80d7e71a-26e8-4bc1-b355-e9702db2785c.jpg	https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/infinite-industries-event-images/uploads/social/80d7e71a-26e8-4bc1-b355-e9702db2785c_social.jpg	29d471f0-047a-11e8-808e-07b6d0fe568b	none	405 Rose St, Lexington, Kentucky 40506	me@me.me	\N	University of Kentucky Opera Theatre presents "Madama Butterfly" by Giacomo Puccini	<p><span style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51);">University of Kentucky Opera Theatre presents&nbsp;</span><strong style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51);"><em>"Madama Butterfly"</em></strong><span style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51);">&nbsp;by Giacomo Puccini in the SCFA Concert Hall.</span></p><p><br></p><p><span style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51);">In the 1890’s, at the small house on top of a hill in Nagasaki, Japan, Pinkerton, an officer in the American Navy, has arranged to take a Japanese wife. Sharpless, the American consul, advises Pinkerton that his actions are hasty, but Pinkerton ignores this advice. Pinkerton marries a beautiful geisha named Cio-Cio-San, known as Madam Butterfly.</span></p><p><br></p><p><span style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51);">After their wedding, Pinkerton returns to America. Three years pass but Cio-Cio-San still believes that he will return to her. One day, Sharpless visits her with a letter from Pinkerton, but cannot bring himself to reveal the contents of the letter as Cio-Cio-San looks so happy with their son, of whom Pinkerton knows nothing. After Sharpless leaves, Cio-Cio-San confirms that an American battleship to which Pinkerton is assigned, has entered the port at Nagasaki.</span></p><p><br></p><p><span style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51);">Sharpless appears with Pinkerton and Kate, his new American wife. Pinkerton, overcome with guilt, flees the house, leaving Cio-Cio-San to come in and see only Kate. Realizing the bitter truth, Cio-Cio-San agrees to give her son up, but insists that Pinkerton must return for him. Cio-Cio-San, realizing the shame this situation has brought, returns to her culture's code of honor as Pinkerton runs in, calling out her name.&nbsp;</span></p><p><br></p><p><span style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51);">Reserved Seating. All seats are priced by location. Discounts for UK Faculty and Staff available exclusively through the SCFA ticket office.</span></p>	{}		https://www.etix.com/ticket/p/6317241/madama-butterfly-presented-by-uk-opera-theatre-lexington-singletary-center			http://bit.ly/2XtEF5A	{}	t	2019-01-09 18:55:01.421+00	2019-11-21 13:22:44.174+00	\N
c16b3a40-9da7-11e9-b43e-456ed9f9b823	Cardinal Moments	cardinal-moments	f	[{"end_time": "2019-07-05 20:30:00", "start_time": "2019-07-05 18:00:00", "optional_title": ""}]	https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/infinite-industries-event-images/uploads/f1d7494d-3e1c-4857-be77-90d7bd0b0b07.jpg	https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/infinite-industries-event-images/uploads/social/f1d7494d-3e1c-4857-be77-90d7bd0b0b07_social.jpg	309452f0-9e50-11e9-b43e-456ed9f9b823	none	 638 E Market St, Louisville, 40202, 	nathanielhendrickson@gmail.com	\N	Highlighting artists who have forged their lives on the periphery. Cardinal Moments introduces ideas that are both distinct and unavoidable to everyday life in the ohio valley. Featuring both emerging and established artists, the exhibited works take a historical and poetic glance at regional folk art, video art, collage, music, assemblage, games, drawing, painting and sculpture. Each artist has created works that convey issues with deep resonance to Kentucky and the south, exploring themes from native American identity, post-industrial suburbia, urban culture, feminist liberation, capitalism, built-in-obsolescence, meme-culture, digitization, politics, seasonal change, conspiracy theory, recycling, and the region's ties to production and decay.	<p><strong>Swanson Contemporary to Present <em>Cardinal Moments</em>, an Exhibition Examining Regional Artists on the Periphery from Found to Folk.</strong></p><p><br></p><p><strong>Cardinal Moments</strong></p><p>July 5 – August 10, 2019</p><p>Curated by Nathan Hendrickson</p><p>and Thaniel ion Lee</p><p><br></p><p><strong>Cardinal Moments </strong>Features Works by Marc Anthony Mulligan, Cynthia Norton, Thaniel Ion Lee, Sue Martinez, Jacque Parsley, Julie Baldyga, Donna Shirley, Art Snake, Al Gorman, Yoko Molotov, Matthew Thurber, Keisha Prioleau-Martin, Kevin Payne, Matt McCarren, Lisa Burkhead and Jim Roche.</p><p><br></p><p>“As in many periods leading up to cardinal moments there is, in the air, not only a heavy drumming resonance but another vibration as well, quieter and more delicate, a subtler necessity.” Mario Biagini</p><p><br></p><p><strong>Louisville, KY, July 1, 2019- </strong>Swanson Contemporary to present <em>Cardinal Moments</em>, an exhibition exploring regional artists whose work squints at the dark matter between art and life. Each of the artists in this show have a demanding relationship with the worlds they create, an ethnographic fidelity to keeping their eyes open to notice what’s going on, and a nuanced way of initiating dialogue through their work. </p><p><br></p><p>As the muffin top of the bible belt, the Ohio valley has a unique character. Not quite the south, not quite the north, it’s got all the waywardness of a Midwestern city, tributaries that run south, and a history as complex as any in the region. As Louisville begins to take on the aspect of a hub in the rhizome of the global city, its characteristic rough edge gets smoothed out, cleaned up and plastered over with the wax figure of a backbone. But we all know who keeps the lights on and the infrastructure of the simulacrum streaming in HD. Taking on the underbelly of the deep south, the stigma of white trash, the darkness of digital alienation, and the tried and the true… The ohio valley has as rich a soil as any for new roots to take hold.</p><p><br></p><p>Highlighting artists who have forged their lives on the periphery. <em>Cardinal Moments </em>introduces ideas that are both distinct and unavoidable to everyday life in the ohio valley. Featuring both emerging and established artists, the exhibited works take a historical and poetic glance at regional folk art, video art, collage, music, assemblage, games, drawing, painting and sculpture. Each artist has created works that convey issues with deep resonance to Kentucky and the south, exploring themes from native American identity, post-industrial suburbia, urban culture, feminist liberation, capitalism, built-in-obsolescence, meme-culture, digitization, politics, seasonal change, conspiracy theory, recycling, and the region's ties to production and urbanization. </p><p><br></p><p>On Friday, July 5<sup>th</sup>, from 6pm to 8:30pm, Swanson Contemporary presents a soft opening of the exhibition, all are welcome. The closing reception for <strong>Cardinal Moments</strong> will be on Friday, August 2<sup>nd</sup> from 6pm to 9pm and will feature performances by Cynthia Norton and Yoko Molotov. </p><p><br></p><p><strong>About Swanson Contemporary</strong></p><p>Swanson Contemporary&nbsp;began operating in the spring of 1998 as only the second gallery in what is now referred to as Louisville’s "NuLu" neighborhood.&nbsp;For the past twenty years, the gallery has showcased contemporary national and regional artists with an emphasis on energetic and challenging works in video, installation, photography, conceptual art, painting, performance, and sculpture.</p><p>Hours: Wed – Sat. 12pm – 6pm. And by appointment.</p><p><em style="color: rgb(34, 34, 34);">“Art does not lie down on the bed that is made for it; It runs away as soon as someone says its name; It loves to be incognito.” – Jean Debuffet</em></p>	{}			https://www.facebook.com/events/422950911734742/		http://bit.ly/3475E9j	{}	t	2019-07-03 15:32:24.165+00	2019-11-21 13:29:26.129+00	\N
