ca194bc0-4526-11e9-b43e-456ed9f9b823	Gallery Hop: Lennon Michalski in the GLO Gallery	gallery-hop:-lennon-michalski-in-the-glo-gallery	f	[{"end_time": "2019-03-15 20:00:00", "start_time": "2019-03-15 17:00:00", "optional_title": ""}]	https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/infinite-industries-event-images/uploads/95a5af9f-588f-43db-9215-b5efd4f90cac.jpg	https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/infinite-industries-event-images/uploads/social/95a5af9f-588f-43db-9215-b5efd4f90cac_social.jpg	2c7ae750-f193-4b5f-9893-fa9d56c647ba	none	362 N Martin Luther King Blvd, Lexington KY 40508	me@me.me	\N	Artist Lennon Michalski creates “…imagery of a world where the line between organic and machine becomes blurred” with his deeply compelling large scale paintings.Michalski will be featured in a solo exhibition this spring in the LASC’s Glo Gallery.	<p>Lennon Michalski</p><p><br></p><p>Artist Lennon Michalski creates “…imagery of a world where the line between organic and machine becomes blurred” with his deeply compelling large scale paintings.Michalski will be featured in a solo exhibition this spring in the LASC’s Glo Gallery.  His approach to the process of art making is truly unique and unusual.  Through process, Michalski has developed an aesthetic that is visceral, intuitive, and completely his own.  Painstakingly, Michalski slowly builds multiple layers of pigments and varnish upon large wooden panels.  If you are aware of his art when you come upon it you know it is his even before reading the title card.  Michalski’s art is seductive, inviting and intense.  He uses color to captivate the viewer to explore his multifaceted ideas.  Michalski’s art teeters somewhere between the color field paintings of the abstract expressionists and the covers of 1950’spulp science fiction novels.  This makes perfect sense with Michalski’s background in both fine and digital art.   </p><p><br></p><p>It is through this complicated process that Michalski conveys his ideas as stated in his artist statement: “I am fascinated by how our culture is quickly merging with technology through the advancements of science.  We are forced to innovate at a rapid pace because of injury or the fragile design of a human figure. There is an innate feeling in us that a limb or organ can be replaced or made more effectively and, as a species, we want to advance our bodies past any disability. Scientists and Innovators work to produce a device through bioengineering that capitalizes on replacing or repairing a damaged design, which does the job better than its predecessor.  We are no longer willing to live with handicaps, performing alterations to life with revolutionary technology and biological research to avoid them.”</p><p><br></p><p>Lennon Michalski’s new series of large scale paintings will be on display at the Living Arts and Science Center February 11th through June 22nd.  A Gallery Hop reception will be held on Friday, March 15th and May 17 from 5:00PM to 8:00PM with an artist talk scheduled at 6:00PM during the March 15th Gallery Hop.</p><p><br></p><p><br></p>	{}	https://www.facebook.com/events/2023886754391032				http://bit.ly/2QEQwfJ	{}	t	2019-03-13 00:27:31.324+00	2019-11-21 13:26:29.914+00	\N
