f17aaaa0-5b20-11e9-b43e-456ed9f9b823	Jason Livingston presents Songs of Inexperience: Select Works	jason-livingston-presents-songs-of-inexperience:-select-works	f	[{"end_time": "2019-04-29 22:00:00", "start_time": "2019-04-29 19:00:00", "optional_title": ""}]	https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/infinite-industries-event-images/uploads/4268bdbc-1610-466a-ac4b-538f2f0d6fd1.jpg	https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/infinite-industries-event-images/uploads/social/4268bdbc-1610-466a-ac4b-538f2f0d6fd1_social.jpg	181af060-047a-11e8-808e-07b6d0fe568b	none	167 W Main St, Lexington, KY 40507	me@me.me	\N	SONGS OF INEXPERIENCE: SELECT WORKS BY JASON LIVINGSTON	<p>SONGS OF INEXPERIENCE: SELECT WORKS BY JASON LIVINGSTON</p><p><br></p><p>Jason Livingston’s films consider public spaces physical, public and digital.  This selection of shorts touches on several themes that run through his work, and abandons chronology, remixing his own films and videos to better unearth questions around the commons and how we may sing at the end of the world.</p><p><br></p><p>Shale Raga | video, 4:31, 2015</p><p>Set to an excerpt of Don Cherry's Malkauns from his border-erasing 1975 album, Brown Rice, Shale Raga extracts corporate video toward resistance a la carbon-based capitalist sorcery, in</p><p>this case EcoShale technology, which is patented by Alberta-based Red Leaf Resoures, Inc. and promises to "revolutionize" oil shale production in the Book Cliffs of eastern Utah.</p><p><br></p><p>ACID REIGN | video, 4:30, 2012</p><p>Combining archival/found footage, treated images and diaristic Hi-8 video, ACID REIGN explores the ongoing battle between human beings' technologies of control and other life forms. In this case, animals re-inhabit a post-human urban landscape.</p><p><br></p><p>The End | video, 4, 1998</p><p>Culled from a collection of duplications. Dyspeptic pop for the apocalyptic generation.</p><p><br></p><p>Copy &amp; Past | video, 6:04, 2013</p><p>Found images and text from online matchmaking sites are anagrammed by poet Dora Malech to produce uncanny digital desires.</p><p><br></p><p>The Two Boys: | video, 8:51, 1999</p><p>Greek goddesses, sailors and dolphins collide in the mind of an amateur cameraman. Memories upended across ocean waters.</p><p><br></p><p><a href="https://www.facebook.com/hashtag/rushes" target="_blank" style="color: rgb(54, 88, 153);">#RUSHES</a> | 16mm / video, 11:52, 2015</p><p>An in-camera 16mm edit of the 1st anniversary /birthday/funeral of OWS in New York City, as seen from an embedded role in the Jellyfish Brigade, an ad hoc affinity group formed to participate in the day's event. Bold impact fonts compliment and countervail the images toward a warm antagonism.</p><p><br></p><p>Your Healing is Killing Me | Tisa Bryant and Jason Livingston video, 3:45, 2018</p><p>Based on the performance manifesto, Your Healing is Killing Me, by Virginia Grise, Bryant and Livingston's video was produced as part of the workshop in the 2018 ImageTextImage program.</p><p><br></p><p>Ancient Sunshine | 16mm / video, 16, 2019</p><p>The film draws on 16mm, iPhone video, and field recordings I’ve assembled from a handful of research trips to Arizona, Colorado, and Utah. Scholar Joel Achenbach uses the term “ancient sunshine” to describe the fossil fuels buried and trapped beneath the surface of the ground. From location shooting in remote mines to county fairs to interviews with committed defenders of the Earth, Ancient Sunshine declares resistance to the few who benefit from extraction, and poetically</p><p>explores relations between the majority of us who eek out an increasingly precarious survival. Purchasing power drops as parts per million increase; a single film cannot remedy this global problem. What cinema offers us is a multi-dimensional practice to collectively express and analyze and organize our way to better conditions.</p><p><br></p>	{}			https://www.facebook.com/events/263798057864874		http://bit.ly/2pxv4Oy	{}	t	2019-04-09 23:41:05.994+00	2019-11-21 13:27:05.881+00	\N
719ba700-f97b-11e8-adae-15fd18a0c793	Art Talk | Hasan Elahi and Laurie Frick	art-talk-|-hasan-elahi-and-laurie-frick	f	[{"end_time": "2019-01-24 19:00:00", "start_time": "2019-01-24 18:00:00", "optional_title": ""}]	https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/infinite-industries-event-images/uploads/f025fcb6-7a0d-41ea-9166-a0b4ee7046aa.jpg		54348750-047a-11e8-808e-07b6d0fe568b	none	300 N Broadway, Lexington, KY 40508	me@me.me	\N	You’re Being Followed: A Discussion about Data Prediction, Privacy, and Digital Tracking with artists Hasan Elahi and Laurie Frick, moderated by Dr. Emily Goodman, Carrick Theater, followed by a reception in the Morlan Gallery	<p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">You’re Being Followed: A Discussion about Data Prediction, Privacy, and Digital Tracking with artists Hasan Elahi and Laurie Frick, moderated by Dr. Emily Goodman, Carrick Theater, followed by a reception in the Morlan Gallery</span></p><p><br></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">This is a part of Morlan Gallery's "Data, Mine" exhibition, featuring the data-driven artwork of Hasan Elahi and Laurie Frick.</span></p><p><br></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">Data, Mine opens January 16 and runs through February 19, 2019. Gallery hours are weekdays, noon to 5 p.m. Additional hours listed below.</span></p><p><br></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">ABOUT THE EXHIBITION</span></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">Data,Mine features the data-driven artwork of Hasan Elahi and Laurie Frick. The exhibition title references the methodology and relationship each artist has with data. In the early 2000s, Elahi started an elaborate project in self-surveillance when he was mistakenly put on a terrorist watch list. His digital work examines issues of surveillance, citizenship, migration, and the challenges of borders and frontiers. Laurie Frick, an artist with a business background, anticipates the future of data and envisions a time when personal data is a unique glimpse into our hidden personalities. By analyzing her life patterns, such as sleep and daily tasks, Frick has created a body of personal data she then translates into vibrant works created from a variety of media, such as leather, wood, and watercolors. Frick is currently mining data from the dating website, Ok,Cupid to create visual patterns helping people to understand one another better.</span></p><p><br></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">SPECIAL EVENTS AND HOURS</span></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">Lexington Gallery Hop | Friday, Jan. 18, 5-8 p.m.</span></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">Closed Monday, January 21 for MLK Day</span></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">Art Talk with Laurie Frick and Hasan Elahi |Thursday, Jan. 24, 6-7 p.m.―You’re Being Followed: A Discussion about Data Prediction, Privacy, and Digital Tracking with Artists Hasan Elahi and Laurie Frick, moderated by Dr. Emily Goodman, Carrick Theater, followed by a reception in the Morlan Gallery</span></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">Evening Hours | Saturday, Feb. 16, 6:30-7:30 p.m.</span></p>	{}			https://www.facebook.com/events/199961284225135/		http://bit.ly/37iHcnk	{}	t	2018-12-06 17:22:01.713+00	2019-11-21 13:27:01.526+00	\N
7ecf6430-76c0-11e9-b43e-456ed9f9b823	Gallery Hop Opening: Miniature Invitational	gallery-hop-opening:-miniature-invitational	f	[{"end_time": "2019-05-17 20:00:00", "start_time": "2019-05-17 17:00:00", "optional_title": ""}]	https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/infinite-industries-event-images/uploads/21501c43-e8a7-4b58-82e0-8b06432e1ff3.jpg	https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/infinite-industries-event-images/uploads/social/21501c43-e8a7-4b58-82e0-8b06432e1ff3_social.jpg	2c7ae750-f193-4b5f-9893-fa9d56c647ba	none	362 N Martin Luther King Blvd, Lexington KY 40508	me@me.me	\N	Invited area artists asked to create miniature versions of their art will be featured in this unique group exhibition of art produced to a minuscule scale	<p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">There is a long history of artists using scale to alter their work.  For many artists, the practice of creating miniature versions of their art assists in faster production and often makes work more affordable for patrons. </span></p><p><br></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">The term ‘miniature’ has its origins in medieval illuminated manuscripts (476AD-1492).  Although these works were often small in size, the word ‘miniature’; was derived from the Latin word miniare meaning ‘to color with minium'. This was a reference to the red lead pigment often used in the decorative lettering found in manuscripts of the period.  Through this association, the word ‘miniature’ began to be used to refer to smaller scale art.</span></p><p><br></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">In the 1700’s, amateur artists started painted miniature portraits on ivory using water colors.  Before photography, this practice became so popular that soon academically trained artists began producing ‘miniature’ portraits for the eager public.  This practice continued until photography replaced it.</span></p><p><br></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">In the modern era, the Dadaist Marcel Duchamp (1887-1968) created ‘miniature’ versions of his major paintings, drawings, and sculptures for his mini portable museum Boîte-en-valise (Box in a Valise).  In the 1970’s, ceramist Charles Simonds produced small adobe dwellings in the crevasses of abandon buildings throughout the world for the unaware public to find.</span></p><p><br></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">Invited area artists asked to create miniature versions of their art will be featured in this unique group exhibition of art produced to a minuscule scale.  Participating artists include: Steve Armstrong, Diane Kahlo, Mary Rezny, Robert Morgan, Amy Chase, Rob Bridges, Blake Eames, Mike Goodlett, Patrick Smith, Kate Sprengnether, Marco Logsdon, Guy Mendes, Ruth Adams, Mollie Rabiner, Hunter Stamps, Carleton Wing, Lawrence Tarpey, JerielleHanlo,KiptooTarus, Rae Goodwin, Lori Larusso,Mia Cinelli, Jennifer Reis,Ed Franklin, Stacey Chinn, Nathan Zamarron, Elizabeth Mesa-Gaido,Georgia Henkel, Arturo Alonzo Sandoval, and Charles Ellis. </span></p>	{}			https://www.facebook.com/events/2285321961683161		http://bit.ly/340AnVM	{}	t	2019-05-15 03:21:14.484+00	2019-11-21 13:27:02.608+00	\N
