e4de3940-5fe1-11e9-b43e-456ed9f9b823	Andy Uhrich presents films from Edward & Naomi Feil Collection	andy-uhrich-presents-films-from-edward-&-naomi-feil-collection	f	[{"end_time": "2019-04-22 22:00:00", "start_time": "2019-04-22 19:00:00", "optional_title": ""}]	https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/infinite-industries-event-images/uploads/1717d93c-9142-4063-9c3d-3ce7bf7b1cfe.jpg		181af060-047a-11e8-808e-07b6d0fe568b	none	167 W Main St, Lexington, KY 40507	em.fribu@gmail.com	\N	Art cinema / medical training films presented by I.U. film archivist Andy Uhrich.	<p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">Andy Uhrich, film archivist at Indiana University Libraries' Moving Image Archive (IULMIA) presents selections from the Edward and Naomi Feil Collection. All are about caring for people with dementia or suffering from aging.</span></p><p><br></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">When Naomi and Ed Feil began making medical training films together in the mid 1960s they elevated a utilitarian genre to an art form. Ed, who had been working as an industrial filmmaker for over a decade, brought his love of art cinema; Naomi, a social worker who practiced what she calls Validation Theory, brought a patient-centered approach to medical care. She also acts in three of these films and thanks her extensive experience with therapeutic role-play she brings an honesty and humanity to her roles that rivals the best method actors.</span></p><p><br></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">These four films focus on a progressive form of elder care and caring for unresponsive patients. They are unique films. They have all the charms of low-budget sponsored, and even underground, filmmaking, the aesthetic aspirations of the new waves that were sweeping world cinema at the time, the raw intensity seen in the films of Cassavetes, and the utopian idea that cinema can get to you empathize with others. ​</span></p><p><br></p><p><strong style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">Program</strong><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">:</span></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">Where Life Still Means Living | 1964, 26 minutes, 16mm</span></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">The Inner World of Aphasia | 1968, 24 minutes, 16mm, National Film Preservation Foundation - preservation copy</span></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">A New Life for Rose (excerpt) | 1973, 8 minutes, digital transfer</span></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">Marge the Blamer | 1988, 17 minutes, 16mm</span></p><p><br></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">The Feils, who gained prominence in 2015 when the Librarian of Congress named their 1968 docudrama “The Inner World of Aphasia” to the National Film Registry, created educational and promotional films from the 1940s through the 1990s.</span></p>	{}			https://www.facebook.com/events/277462526493944/		http://bit.ly/2NYbe8s	{}	t	2019-04-16 00:52:22.357+00	2019-11-21 13:27:22.41+00	\N
74f7f600-24ec-11e9-b43e-456ed9f9b823	The Films of Dorothy Arzner	the-films-of-dorothy-arzner	f	[{"end_time": "2019-03-18 21:00:00", "start_time": "2019-03-18 19:00:00", "optional_title": ""}]	https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/infinite-industries-event-images/uploads/a436a3a1-864d-44b4-a2e0-a87a9391658e.jpg	https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/infinite-industries-event-images/uploads/social/a436a3a1-864d-44b4-a2e0-a87a9391658e_social.jpg	446e9860-047a-11e8-808e-07b6d0fe568b	none	140 E Main St, Lexington, Kentucky 40507	me@me.me	\N	The Bride Wore Red (1937, Starring Joan Crawford, Franchot Tone, Robert Young, and Billie Burke)	<p>The Bride Wore Red (1937, Starring Joan Crawford, Franchot Tone, Robert Young, and Billie Burke)</p><p><br></p><p>In honor of Women's History Month, the Lexington Film League and the Lexington Public Library are pleased to present a free weekly screening series dedicated to cinematic pioneer Dorothy Arzner.</p><p><br></p><p>Arzner was both the first woman to become a member of the Director's Guild of America and the first to direct a sound picture. As a pioneer of the "talkie" she invented the first ever boom mic. She also launched the careers of some of the most celebrated actresses in Hollywood history with her emphasis on fiercely independent roles for women. Yet for decades she was largely forgotten in film histories written largely by men.</p><p><br></p><p>Fortunately, her films have screened more widely in the past several years and the world is finally acknowledging the importance of Arzner's singular vision.</p><p><br></p>	{}			https://www.facebook.com/events/606828386427837		http://bit.ly/2O639hW	{}	t	2019-01-31 00:09:20.481+00	2019-11-21 13:25:11.847+00	\N
