e124dda0-41e4-11ea-abf2-8dc9e627a96d	The Films of Gordon Parks	the-films-of-gordon-parks	f	[{"end_time": "2020-02-01T21:00:00.000Z", "start_time": "2020-02-01T19:00:00.000Z", "optional_title": ""}, {"end_time": "2020-02-08T21:00:00.000Z", "start_time": "2020-02-08T19:00:00.000Z", "optional_title": ""}, {"end_time": "2020-02-15T21:00:00.000Z", "start_time": "2020-02-15T19:00:00.000Z", "optional_title": ""}, {"end_time": "2020-02-22T21:00:00.000Z", "start_time": "2020-02-22T19:00:00.000Z", "optional_title": ""}]	https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/infinite-industries-event-images/uploads/44f90a9a-ba39-4161-b69d-a4541e8d9fa4.jpg	https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/infinite-industries-event-images/uploads/social/44f90a9a-ba39-4161-b69d-a4541e8d9fa4_social.jpg	446e9860-047a-11e8-808e-07b6d0fe568b	Free	140 E Main St, Lexington, Kentucky 40507	lexfilmleague@gmail.com	\N	The Lexington Public Library and the Lexington Film League are pleased to present a free weekly screening series dedicated to the work of photographer/filmmaker/writer/musician/genius Gordon Parks.	<p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">“He is often called a ‘Renaissance man’ because he worked in so many different media, but I like to refer to him as a humanitarian artist who used whatever medium he could to have an impact.” </span></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">- Peter Kunhardt, Jr., Executive Director of the Gordon Parks Foundation</span></p><p><br></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">Born on November 30, 1912 in Fort Scott, Kansas, Gordon Parks is best known as one of the greatest photographers of the 20th Century. But the sensitive eye, compelling personal style, and profound humanity that first made him a giant of photojournalism translated equally well to the silver screen. We are thrilled to have an opportunity to screen three of his most acclaimed films, THE LEARNING TREE, LEADBELLY, and SHAFT, as well as a documentary about his life and work.</span></p><p><br></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">Saturday, February 1 @ 2 pm: HALF PAST AUTUMN: THE LIFE AND WORKS OF GORDON PARKS (2000) An intimate look at the life and career of Gordon Parks and his work in photography, literature, journalism, music, publishing, and film told through the lens of the 1990's travelling retrospective of the same name.</span></p><p><br></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">Saturday, February 8 @ 2 pm: THE LEARNING TREE (1969) A landmark motion picture based on Parks' semi-autobiographical novel of the same name, The Learning Tree was the first major Hollywood film to be helmed by a black director. In addition to writing and directing this coming-of-age tale set in his home state of Kansas in the 1920's, Parks produced the picture and composed the soundtrack. </span></p><p><br></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">Saturday, February 15 @ 2 pm: LEADBELLY (1976) A biography of Huddie Ledbetter (Roger E. Mosley), this drama follows the life of the highly influential  blues singer and guitarist better known as "Leadbelly." </span></p><p><br></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">Saturday, February 22 @ 2 pm: SHAFT (1971) John Shaft (Richard Roundtree) is the man that would risk his neck for his brother man. He's the cat that won't cop out when there's danger all about. Can ya dig it?</span></p>	{}	www.lexingtonfilmleague.org		https://www.facebook.com/events/1037218886657548/?event_time_id=1037218893324214		http://bit.ly/3aLfyS1	{}	t	2020-01-28 15:43:08.554+00	2020-01-29 14:55:34.274+00	\N
247f7540-6339-11ea-9d91-8b9a74a66ddd	Kentucky Women Fiddlers	kentucky-women-fiddlers-at-the-niles-gallery,-march-13,-1-p.m.	f	[{"end_time": "2020-03-13T18:00:00.000Z", "start_time": "2020-03-13T17:00:00.000Z", "optional_title": ""}]	https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/infinite-industries-event-images/uploads/2dc22090-8a09-4523-9ea9-1d68caa85a29.jpg	https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/infinite-industries-event-images/uploads/social/2dc22090-8a09-4523-9ea9-1d68caa85a29_social.jpg	c7d4b110-d8a1-11e9-b43e-456ed9f9b823	none	160 Patterson Dr, Lexington, 40506, University of Kentucky	me@me.me	\N	Anna Harrod, Maggie Lander, Karen Jones, Linda Jean Stokley, and Deborah Payne will explore their fiddling styles at the Niles Gallery from 1 - 2 p.m, Friday, March 13, as part of the Appalachian Studies Conference hosted by University of Kentucky.	<p>Anna Harrod, Maggie Lander, Karen Jones, Linda Jean Stokley, and Deborah Payne will explore their fiddling styles at the Niles Gallery from 1 - 2 p.m, Friday, March 13, as part of the Appalachian Studies Conference hosted by University of Kentucky. Free and open to the public.</p><p><br></p><p>Anna Harrod grew up running and a scraping her knees in the hills of Owen County, Kentucky surrounded by banjos, fiddles and singing, but did not follow her early influences until she returned from a stint in West Virginia. She rediscovered those spirits deep within her bones and began fiddling “those squirrelly mountain tunes”.  She lives in Lexington where she grows hemp, mixes drinks, and “plays in an all lady band called the Possum Queens”.</p><p><br></p><p>Maggie Lander is a Lexington fiddler that traverses genres with ease. Raised on the traditional tunes of Kentucky music, she went on to be classically trained, and to play jazz, bluegrass, and Arabic music. She is a studio musician, a former member of the Woodsongs Old Time Radio Hour house band, and currently tours with the Nashville Celts playing the music of Scotland and Ireland. </p><p><br></p><p>Deborah Payne is a fiddler from Berea, Kentucky. Her musical lilt is influenced by the region's rich traditions of bluegrass, old time, and folk dance music. She performs with Sam Gleaves and recently recorded a CD with him entitled Welcome as the Flowers in May. In the summer, she teaches fiddle at Berea’s Singing Bird Music School.</p><p><br></p><p>Karen Jones, fiddler with the Reel World String Band for 39 years and TDH4 a/k/a/ Tall Dark and Handsome for 26 years, has toured throughout Canada, Italy and the US. Still performing, she often hosts an old time jam, a jazz jam and, through Musicworks Lexington, teaches young students to play fiddle.</p><p><br></p><p>Linda Jean Stokley,  fiddler from Woodford County, and member of the well known Local Honeys. The Local Honeys just returned to Kentucky from a extensive tour of the British Isles. Linda Jean is a graduate of the Traditional Music Program at MSU and apprenticed with Master Fiddler Jesse Wells-- 2015 Folk Art Grant. When she is not touring  she teaches at Cowan Creek Mt. Music School and Central Music Academy.</p><p><br></p>	{}			https://www.facebook.com/events/207715600422458/		http://bit.ly/2wPmlKA	{}	t	2020-03-11 01:39:26.619+00	2020-03-11 13:24:34.775+00	\N
