02751d30-3673-11ea-9d77-193829f642f5	Unsettled - Opening Reception	unsettled-opening-reception	f	[{"end_time": "2020-01-17T01:00:00.000Z", "start_time": "2020-01-16T23:00:00.000Z", "optional_title": ""}]	https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/infinite-industries-event-images/uploads/565c6ad3-c5df-4d6c-88b1-6dc9718786f1.jpg	https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/infinite-industries-event-images/uploads/social/565c6ad3-c5df-4d6c-88b1-6dc9718786f1_social.jpg	637de4f0-d3c3-403a-b57a-8975e242763c	none	400 E College St, Georgetown, KY 40324	savannah@uky.edu	\N	"Unsettled", a solo exhibition by printmaker Liz Shepherd, will be on view in the Wilson Gallery January 16-February 22. 	<p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">"Unsettled", a solo exhibition by printmaker Liz Shepherd, will be on view in the Wilson Gallery January 16-February 22. An opening reception with the artist will take place Thursday January 16, 6-8 PM. </span></p><p><br></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">Liz Shepherd is a sculptor and printmaker. In many of her works, three-dimensional objects inexplicably drop out of thin air and accumulate in heaps. </span></p><p><br></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">This exhibition, Unsettled, at Georgetown College, includes a large installation of life-sized silkscreen images of furniture which tumble down the wall. </span></p><p><br></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">The first iteration of this body of work was created at the invitation of the Fitchburg Art Museum for “Interior Effects”, an exhibition celebrating the history of furniture making in the Fitchburg/Gardner Massachusetts area.  This installation featured wall-mounted, silkscreened plywood couches, chairs and ottomans appropriated from the Heywood-Wakefield furniture catalog, using color and pattern to reinforce the advertising of furniture based on male and female cultural norms.  For practical reasons (the plywood pieces being too costly to ship) and out of the pure joy of printmaking, the entire body of work has been reprinted on fabric for this show. </span></p><p><br></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">Up and Out, silkscreen printed ladders on fabric, celebrate an optimistic disregard for gravity and utility. They are a representation of the effort to rise above earthly entanglements. This essentially Buddhist view is an expression of the idea that suffering is a result of attachments, not only to things (that inevitably break or wear out) or ideology, but also to relationships. </span></p><p><br></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">The Unsettled theme also refers to the artist’s ongoing concern for displaced people. The immigrant images in this exhibition are just a few in a large body of work that was originally inspired by a trip to Berlin. The work is ongoing as the issue of immigration continues to unsettle and divides our nation. </span></p><p><br></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">Liz Shepherd, a sculptor and printmaker, received her MFA from the School of the Museum of Fine Arts (Boston)/ Tufts University in 2006.   She is a member of the Boston Sculptors Gallery and is a past of the President of the Boston Printmakers. In 2014, she participated in exhibitions at the Hanoi (Vietnam) Contemporary Arts Center, the Q’orikancha Museum in Cusco, Peru, the Icelandic Printmakers Gallery in Reykjanik. Shepherd has also been included in exhibitions of the Royal Academy of Painters and Printmakers at the Bankside Gallery in London and with the Los Angeles Printmakers.  In 2015 she was awarded a Traveling Fellowship from the School of the Museum of Fine Arts, Boston.  Shepherd was a resident artist at the Society of Arts and Crafts in Boston in 2017.</span></p><p><br></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">Shepherd’s work is in the permanent collections of the Museum of Fine Arts, Boston, The Edinburgh College of Art (Scotland), Syracuse University, The Bernard A. Zuckerman Museum of Art in Kennesaw, Georgia, the Hanoi (Vietnam) Contemporary Arts Center, the Boston Public Library, Children’s Hospital, Boston and numerous corporate and private collections.</span></p>	{}			https://www.facebook.com/events/2755039094562128/		http://bit.ly/381alDg	{}	t	2020-01-14 02:10:17.953+00	2020-01-14 21:34:08.608+00	\N
