2e0909c0-bef5-11e9-b43e-456ed9f9b823	Opening Reception: April Wright Ephemeral Dwellings	opening-reception:-april-wright-ephemeral-dwellings	f	[{"end_time": "2019-08-29 21:00:00", "start_time": "2019-08-29 18:00:00", "optional_title": ""}]	https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/infinite-industries-event-images/uploads/6abdf782-26cc-41b3-bb84-62f6f9bd132d.jpg	https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/infinite-industries-event-images/uploads/social/6abdf782-26cc-41b3-bb84-62f6f9bd132d_social.jpg	197d2c60-6b9a-412f-9cfc-468e25a5c9cc	none	720 Bryan Ave. Lexington KY	apriljwrightsculptor@gmail.com	\N	Join us for the reception of April Wright's one-week pop-up exhibition of sculpture and installation work, Ephemeral Dwellings!    BYOB 21+ Free and open to the public! 	<p>Join us for the reception of April Wright's one-week pop-up exhibition of sculpture and installation work, Ephemeral Dwellings!&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>BYOB 21+ Free and open to the public!&nbsp;</p><p>Show is up 8-27-8-31 Gallery Hours Wed-Fri 5-8, Saturday 12-3</p><p><br></p><p>April's Statement:&nbsp;Escaping into a constant need to search, deconstruct, repurpose, accumulate, and repair; I build and re-build installations that long for stability. Using humble, discarded materials, I connect personal narratives about home, relationships, memory, and identity. Through this work, I weave in moments of vulnerability and strength.&nbsp;Some of the discarded materials that are used include shredded clothing; recycled paper broken down from previously made shelters and reclaimed clay shavings. While reflecting on the intrinsic memories of home and my personal narrative that these divisive materials possess, I reform them into building materials that are precious, fragile and flawed. The structures I build from them are ephemeral, and the objects created are disjointed, rendered purposeless. Building from forgotten materials, I grasp at memories of the past while reflecting on the fragmented parts of the present.&nbsp;--&nbsp;See more of April's work at https://www.apriljwright.org/</p>	{}	http://www.parachutefactorylex.com/about.html				http://bit.ly/2XBAtkk	{}	t	2019-08-15 00:39:46.013+00	2019-11-21 13:30:46.538+00	\N
bd7e2a80-c2a7-11e9-b43e-456ed9f9b823	Opening Reception for Comfort Zone by Joe Nanashe 	opening-reception-for-comfort-zone-by-joe-nanashe-	f	[{"end_time": "2019-08-22 19:00:00", "start_time": "2019-08-22 17:00:00", "optional_title": ""}]	https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/infinite-industries-event-images/uploads/289d86bf-37c2-4fa1-924a-527d4ce3410c.jpg	https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/infinite-industries-event-images/uploads/social/289d86bf-37c2-4fa1-924a-527d4ce3410c_social.jpg	637de4f0-d3c3-403a-b57a-8975e242763c	none	400 E College St, Georgetown, KY 40324	savannah.wills@uky.edu	\N	An opening reception for Comfort Zone, a site-specific installation by New York-based artist, Joe Nanashe, will take place in the Wilson Art Gallery on Thursday August 22, 5-7 PM. 	<p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">An opening reception for Comfort Zone, a site-specific installation by New York-based artist, Joe Nanashe, will take place in the Wilson Art Gallery on Thursday August 22, 5-7 PM. </span></p><p><br></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">Nanashe: "My work is an exploration of life, death, power, violence, sex, perception, and humor. My practice is a game of connect-the-dots between disparate ideas. It slips down the rabbit hole of history to mine imagery, art, language, and recontextualize the everyday. I look for the sacred in the profane, the astounding in the ordinary. It is kaleidoscopic, collapsing the microcosmic and the macrocosmic into a singular moment of recognition, a slap in the face, and involuntary spasm of laughter in the face of annihilation. </span></p><p><br></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">A brick or cell repeated creates an overwhelming, complex structure. The single action, image, object repeated becomes a purgatorial space where time is infinite and meaningless. The revolution of the assembly line deconstructed and compartmentalized human action to the point that repetitive stress disorder became a way of life. Video exacerbated this in the 20th century, and spread nicely into 21st technology and communication. The body in my work is a tool that manipulates and is manipulated by the technology, tools, and/or devices for recording. </span></p><p><br></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">I explore the space between the art and the eye. This is a liminal space where things get lost, distorted destroyed, before the message enters the body. The objects are themselves and something else. A switch is flipped in the brain and those innocent or innocuous elements become something threatening, grand, alien, or absurd. I fascinated by those moments between the childlike and horrifying. </span></p><p><br></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">Appropriation plays a large role in my practice.  In a sense, all of the elements in my work are pulled from existing sources. Tools, images, music, sounds, words, pop culture and high art. They evoke a common experience of existence, of utilization in the real world. Objects are defined by their function and their direct interaction with the body. Removed from the real, they become an examination of mortality, of breathing, being, working, of communication and perception. These works are the echoes of human experience as we slip through time."</span></p><p><br></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">Joe Nanashe was born in Akron, Ohio. The city’s post-industrial landscape and emphasis on manual labor influenced the repetitive, task-driven nature of his work. He received his BFA from the University of Akron in 2003 and his MFA from Rutgers in 2005. A multimedia artist, Nanashe creates works that confront the viewer with issues of violence, control, meaning, humor, perception, and the body. His videos have been shown in multiple editions of the Chicago, New York, Boston, and Lausanne Underground Film Festivals. His drawings, sculpture, photographs, and sound work have been exhibited at the Parrish Art Museum and Islip Art Museum on Long Island; Eric Firestone and QF Gallery in East Hampton, Catinca Tabacaru, Fresh Window, Jim Kempner Fine Art and Garis &amp;Hahn Gallery in New York City, as well as internationally in Argentina, Canada, Germany, Japan, The Netherlands, Russia, and Switzerland. He was a 2105 Finalist for the New York Foundation for the Arts Artist Fellowship in Interdisciplinary Art. His solo exhibition, “Joe Nanashe, American Vanitas” opened at Victori+Mo Gallery September 2016. Joe currently lives and works in Ridgewood, NY.</span></p>	{}			https://www.facebook.com/events/493607747880717		http://bit.ly/2KEVsxm	{}	t	2019-08-19 17:35:30.601+00	2019-11-21 13:30:47.636+00	\N
908fbe90-c2a6-11e9-b43e-456ed9f9b823	Sarah Zapata Closing Reception/Gallery Hop	sarah-zapata-closing-reception/gallery-hop	f	[{"end_time": "2019-09-20 20:00:00", "start_time": "2019-09-20 17:00:00", "optional_title": ""}]	https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/infinite-industries-event-images/uploads/91d03a90-da59-463b-a82d-e976488c1dd4.jpg	https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/infinite-industries-event-images/uploads/social/91d03a90-da59-463b-a82d-e976488c1dd4_social.jpg	d0858cc0-0478-11e8-808e-07b6d0fe568b	none	193 N Limestone, Lexington, KY 40507	me@me.me	\N	On view at Institute 193, for the first exhibition of her work in the South, Zapata is presenting an intimate series of watercolor studies made as references for her larger works	<p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">Sarah Zapata: Speculative Monuments</span></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">August 7 – September 20</span></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">Closing Reception: September 20, 5 – 8 PM</span></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);"> </span></p><p><br></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">Sarah Zapata’s weavings and textile-based sculptures have been described as monuments for alternate or future worlds or ruins from a past one. On view at Institute 193, for the first exhibition of her work in the South, Zapata is presenting an intimate series of watercolor studies made as references for her larger works. The drawings are one part of the artist’s research-steeped practice which routinely engages with the personal and collective histories tied to her intersecting identities as a queer, Peruvian-American raised in an Evangelical Christian household in Texas.</span></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);"> </span></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">The works are presented at 193 in the context of a region divided over the appropriateness and continued display of the monuments and memorials dedicated to leaders and fallen soldiers of the Confederacy. Just two years ago, after advocacy lead by Take Back Cheapside, Lexington’s city council voted to relocate two such monuments dedicated to John C. Breckenridge and John Hunt Morgan, both Generals in the Confederate Army. Notably, the Lexington monuments, like many similar monuments elsewhere in the South, were built at the height of the Jim Crow Era, not immediately after the Civil War. Unlike most of the monuments, they were built in a state that never joined the Confederacy. Other symbols of the Confederacy, especially its flag, have been used as racist dog whistles, both in former Confederate states and in other parts of the country with no connection to the Confederacy whatsoever.  Similarly, these monuments functioned (and many elsewhere continue to function) as sites of publicly sanctioned intimidation of brown and black people rather than acting in good faith as legitimate memorials for the dead. The organizations that built them, in the end, were able to continue advocating for the racial dynamics of a failed state under the guise of mourning and remembrance.</span></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);"> </span></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">In her work, too, Zapata recognizes failure not as an end, but as a part of an ongoing process.  The translation from two-dimensional drawings to three-dimensional sculptures and installations is rarely straightforward and sometimes unsuccessful. Colors change, and forms are reconfigured in response to the needs of a space, sometimes being abandoned altogether. The watercolor studies for future sculptures, some of which were eventually realized and exhibited, of course, have distinctly different goals than the Civil War monuments being discussed in the South today. Instead of reinforcing the positions of a group already in power, they envision an alternate present or possible future whose monuments pay homage to different communities, histories, and ways of being.</span></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);"> </span></p><p><br></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);"> </span></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">For press inquiries contact:</span></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">Paul Michael Brown</span></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">paul@institute193.org</span></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">270 925 2311</span></p><p><br></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">Special thanks to </span><a href="https://www.facebook.com/JustFundKY/" target="_blank" style="color: rgb(56, 88, 152); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">JustFundKY</a><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);"> for their support of this exhibition!</span></p>	{}			https://www.facebook.com/events/701916876951559		http://bit.ly/33dMCgw	{}	t	2019-08-19 17:27:05.722+00	2019-11-21 13:30:50.083+00	\N
