511e8950-dc9e-11e9-b43e-456ed9f9b823	Contact Improvisation Class and Jam	contact-improvisation-class-and-jam	f	[{"end_time": "2019-09-29 16:00:00", "start_time": "2019-09-29 14:00:00", "optional_title": ""}, {"end_time": "2019-10-06 16:00:00", "start_time": "2019-10-06 14:00:00", "optional_title": ""}, {"end_time": "2019-10-13 16:00:00", "start_time": "2019-10-13 14:00:00", "optional_title": ""}, {"end_time": "2019-10-20 16:00:00", "start_time": "2019-10-20 14:00:00", "optional_title": ""}, {"end_time": "2019-10-27 16:00:00", "start_time": "2019-10-27 14:00:00", "optional_title": ""}]	https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/infinite-industries-event-images/uploads/62d2fd7f-1687-42b5-9096-ef4317fe7686.jpg	https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/infinite-industries-event-images/uploads/social/62d2fd7f-1687-42b5-9096-ef4317fe7686_social.jpg	28eed072-7ef6-4726-b3a4-bc7bbe0ee3a1	Suggested donation ~$5	141 E Main St, Lexington, KY 40507	contactimprovlex@gmail.com	\N	No previous experience necessary! Contact Improvisation is a dance/movement/awareness practice where we dance with a partner, without leading or following, but listening to each other, ourselves, and our collective momentum. We practice giving and receiving consent and positive, supportive physical contact and touch. Come play and experiment with us!	<p>A spiral - Momentum - Meeting - Following - Listening - Leaning - Playing - Experimenting - Engaging - Releasing</p><p><br></p><p>Contact Improvisation is an embodied practice where we can learn to meet and interact with another human</p><ul><li>We meet another body and follow a changing point of contact as we are moved through space</li><li>We navigate dynamics and nuances of (mostly) non-verbal interactions</li><li>We practice giving and receiving consent</li><li>We practice setting boundaries for our own bodies and safety and practice respecting others boundaries</li><li>We can play and roll around on the floor together</li><li>We can can lean into each other, we can experience being held and supported and offering this to others</li><li>We learn about the physics of our bodies, the use of levers, ledges and momentum to connect with the earth <em>through</em> another body</li><li>We can experience consensual, non-sexual, physical contact with others</li></ul><p><br></p><p>Contact improvisation has no prescribed steps, movements, lifts, or aesthetic.&nbsp;It is an invitation to explore stillness and movement in your own body, from moment to moment, from week to week, from person to person that you come in contact with. It is a practice that can become a mirror and tool for self knowing and self reflecting, as we can only really know ourselves in relationship to others.</p><p><br></p><p><strong>About This Jam</strong></p><p>This is a new weekly Jam that will come into its shape as it unfolds and progresses, incorporating the needs and desires of those who are interested in the development of this kind of exploration.</p><p><br></p><p>We will be offering a group warm up and some facilitated exercises with changing partners, offering new and experienced dancers new entry points to the dance. We will then transition to an Open Jam where participants are invited to dance with each other as they like, in pairs, in clusters, or alone, to observe, to rest, and enter in and out of dancing. We will usually be dancing without music, to better listen to ourselves and each other.</p><p><br></p><p>No previous experience is necessary. </p><p>Our space is ADA compliant and participants of ANY ability, size, age, income level, background, and racial/gender/religious identity are welcome.&nbsp;</p><p><br></p><p>Please read the Community Agreements, the Timeline of this Jam, and the Practical Instructions before you plan to attend.</p><p>We will have a liability waiver for you to sign in person, assuming physical risk of this activity and confirming that you have read and agree to our Community Agreements.</p><p><br></p><p><strong>Timeline of this Class/Jam</strong></p><p>~ 1.40pm: Arrive - dress - stretch</p><p>~ 2pm: Round of Introductions - orientation and explanation of the Jam</p><p>~ Facilitated group warm up (individual)</p><p>~ Partner exercises to explore technique and mechanics</p><p>~ Group sharing, noticings and questions</p><p>~ Water and bio-break</p><p>~ Begin an open Jam</p><p>~ Group sharing about our experiences</p><p>~ 4pm: End Jam&nbsp;</p><p><br></p><p><strong>Practical Instructions for Attending</strong></p><ul><li>Please arrive before 2 as we will be locking the front doors and moving to a room away from the street</li><li>A suggested donation of $5 per class can be made by cash or Venmo</li><li>Clothing should ideally cover most of your skin, and not be slippery. Cotton is a great. Leave your hands and feet free.&nbsp;</li><li>Kneepads can make it more comfortable to take weight in kneeling positions, especially on hard floors (We will have numerous pairs available for purchase at cost ($13) at each class)</li><li>Please refrain from wearing scented products in consideration of those who have chemical sensitivities. Brush pet dander from your clothes.</li><li>Avoid wearing jewelry, watches, and clothing with buttons.</li><li>Stay home if you have a contagious infection such as a cold or flu. Wear bandaids over cuts and scratches.</li></ul><p><br></p><p><strong>Community Agreements</strong></p><ul><li>Respect people’s pronouns, names, and accommodation needs (includes listening and observing each others boundaries concerning taking breaks, avoiding partner’s injuries, etc)</li><li>Verbal and physical aggression, posturing, harassment, gas-lighting, and other forms of manipulation are not welcome at this jam and will result in exclusion if such behavior is identified</li><li>We will take care of our own safety, physically and emotionally; we will not inhibit others from taking care of their own safety.&nbsp;</li><li>This includes:</li><li class="ql-indent-1">Never locking anyone in a constrained position against their will, or manipulating their body in any way that does not allow them free movement, especially of their hands and feet</li><li class="ql-indent-1">Never inappropriately/sexually touching a partner; it is never okay to intentionally touch anyone’s chest or genitals.</li><li class="ql-indent-1">Never attempting to convince another to do something they do not feel ready to do</li><li class="ql-indent-1">Keeping our bodies soft so that, in the event of a collision, we are less likely to be injured or injure one another</li></ul><p><br></p><p><br></p><p><em>Excerpts of these guidelines and agreements are taken from the “Inclusive Contact Improvisation Jam Guidelines” that Nicole Bindler has compiled for the Jam in Philadelphia.</em></p><p><em>“A Compendium of Contact Improvisation Jam Guidelines and related material from around the world” can be found following this link: </em><a href="https://tinyurl.com/yxa3fstg?fbclid=IwAR2JoFVO2VzpqkMIcyoZvEHIQ-1fqDinBuuVLjGuqMjtUkGfj7I83V81mPQ" target="_blank" style="color: rgb(220, 161, 13);"><em>https://tinyurl.com/yxa3fstg</em></a></p>	{}	https://www.facebook.com/ContactImprovLEX		https://www.facebook.com/events/677787012703227/		http://bit.ly/37nu1BM	{}	t	2019-09-21 18:33:33.543+00	2019-11-21 13:32:27.032+00	\N
