uth, renowned novelist and anthropologist Zora Neale Hurston, exuberant folk artist Clementine Hunter and fervant civil rights worker Fannie Lou Hamer. Text is by Kim Hines. The musical score is drawn from the heartfelt sprituals of the Deep South, the urban exuberance of the Jazz Age and concert music by African American composers including Diane Monroe.  Actress Shinnerrie Jackson plays the four historical characters.</span></p><p><br></p><p><span style="color: rgb(29, 33, 41);">Shinnerrie Jackson has appeared in regional theatre and collegiate theatre in such productions as Guys and Dolls, A Christmas Carol, The Tempest, Much Ado About Nothing, King Lear, All My Sons, The Glass Menagerie, and Raisin in the Sun. Favorite roles include Mama Morton in Chicago (Weathervane Theater), Female Chorus in Electra (Pittsburgh Public Theater), and One Night with Janis Joplin. She has been seen on 30 Rock and in Whit Stillmans’ Damsels in Distress. Ms. Jackson holds an MFA in Acting from the University of Tennessee and a B.M. in Vocal Performance from Oberlin Conservatory. This is her seventh season touring in “Ain’t I a Woman!” Shinnerrie Jackson is a member of Actor’s Equity Association.</span></p>	{}		https://lexingtonlyric.tix.com/Event.aspx?EventCode=1167277	https://www.facebook.com/events/545576432955164/		http://bit.ly/3cjelC2	{}	t	2020-03-02 02:23:23.576+00	2020-03-02 15:15:33.303+00	\N
