be879be0-0a28-11eb-a43d-dfe2af8cac81	Robert C. May Photography Lecture Series: Lynsey Addario	robert-c.-may-photography-lecture-series:-lynsey-addario	f	[{"end_time": "2020-10-09T18:00:00.000Z", "start_time": "2020-10-09T17:00:00.000Z", "optional_title": ""}]	https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/infinite-industries-event-images/uploads/2209bd59-d31d-47b7-970b-ec33778a926c.jpg	https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/infinite-industries-event-images/uploads/social/2209bd59-d31d-47b7-970b-ec33778a926c_social.jpg	764d56c0-abe2-11ea-aa51-cdc3fe7afefa	none	None	dima@me.me	\N	Lynsey Addario has chosen a profession that leads her directly into the midst war zones and humanitarian crises around the world, including Afghanistan, the Congo, Darfur, Iraq, Lebanon, Somalia, South Sudan, and Syria	<p>As a photojournalist, Lynsey Addario has chosen a profession that leads her directly into the midst war zones and humanitarian crises around the world, including Afghanistan, the Congo, Darfur, Iraq, Lebanon, Somalia, South Sudan, and Syria. She has been kidnapped twice: once for a day in Fallujah; another time she was held for a week in Libya. Both times she thought she would be killed. “I believe in these stories; I believe they have to be told. And so I force myself to go to these places. It's not an adrenaline rush and it's not an addiction,” Addario says. “People always ask, like, are you stoic when you're shooting? And I am anything but stoic.”</p><p>What distinguishes her career is the decision Addario made on to focus on the in-depth examination of human rights abuses and especially issues affecting women and children under repressive regimes, often gaining access regions closed to outsiders. She was awarded a MacArthur grant in 2009 and traveled to Afghanistan three times before 9/11 when it was still under Taliban rule; she has examined mother and infant mortality in the developing world; and was part of a New York Times team following the plight of three refugee children displaced in Syria, Ukraine, and South Sudan.</p><p>Addario has won countless major awards, including the Pulitzer Prize for her work on the reporting team for Talibanistan, published in the New York Times Magazine. American Photo magazine named her as one of the five most influential photographers of the past 25 years in 2015 because of how she “changed the way we saw the world’s conflicts,” and Oprah Winfrey recognized her on her Power of Bearing Witness list in 2010. She has written two books: the memoir It’s What I Do; and Of Love and War. She has been featured in Women of Vision: National Geographic Photographers on Assignment and her work has appeared in many leading journals and newspapers.</p><p><br></p><p>This lecture will be presented on Zoom. Please click the link below to join the webinar:</p><p><a href="https://uky.zoom.us/j/85448287269?fbclid=IwAR3LCruSV0CjPYdgeA3ADVEMIYjgtOa-4DGkHxkPRtvPxDJEWEMT9YV2rcw" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" style="color: var(--blue-link);">https://uky.zoom.us/j/85448287269</a></p><p>Or iPhone one-tap:</p><p>US: +13017158592, 85448287269# or +13126266799, 85448287269#</p><p>Or Telephone:</p><p>Dial (for higher quality, dial a number based on your current location):</p><p>US: +1 301 715 8592 or +1 312 626 6799 or +1 646 876 9923 or +1 253 215 8782 or +1 346 248 7799 or +1 669 900 6833</p><p>Webinar ID: 854 4828 7269</p><p>International numbers available:&nbsp;<a href="https://uky.zoom.us/u/kbMVtRe116?fbclid=IwAR08KZmxd9etNrPW-aS7BvOQ9dmdqfa1LZX964JXaCkpdLUH0wYuZqj6SvY" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" style="color: var(--blue-link);">https://uky.zoom.us/u/kbMVtRe116</a></p><p>Zoom is a free service, but if you are a new user, we recommend that you download it to your device prior to the scheduled talks</p>	{}			https://www.facebook.com/events/324024745552385/		https://bit.ly/3nG9ZuD	{}	t	2020-10-09 12:12:47.813+00	2020-10-09 13:00:30.523+00	\N
